Predefined Structural directives
*ngFor
*ngIf
*ngSwitch

Angular does not simply take data and then generate HTML once.
Instead it follows a template → data binding → DOM update process.
Angular HTML Generation Flow

1️⃣ Component provides data

First the component class holds the data.

Example:

export class AppComponent {
  isLoggedIn = true;
  items = ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Mango'];
}

This is the data source.

2️⃣ Angular reads the HTML template

Example template:

<div *ngIf="isLoggedIn">
  Welcome User
</div>

<ul>
  <li *ngFor="let item of items">
    {{item}}
  </li>
</ul>

Angular compiles this template.

3️⃣ Angular converts structural directives

Angular internally rewrites them using ng-template.

Example conversion:

<ng-template [ngIf]="isLoggedIn">
  <div>Welcome User</div>
</ng-template>

<ng-template ngFor let-item [ngForOf]="items">
  <li>{{item}}</li>
</ng-template>
4️⃣ Angular evaluates the data

Angular checks the values from the component.

Example:

isLoggedIn = true
items = ['Apple','Banana','Mango']
5️⃣ Angular generates DOM elements

Based on the data, Angular creates or removes elements.

Generated HTML in the browser DOM:

<div>Welcome User</div>

<ul>
  <li>Apple</li>
  <li>Banana</li>
  <li>Mango</li>
</ul>
Important Concept: Change Detection

Angular constantly watches the data.

If the data changes:

this.items.push("Orange");

Angular automatically updates the DOM.

New DOM:

<li>Apple</li>
<li>Banana</li>
<li>Mango</li>
<li>Orange</li>

So Angular is dynamic, not one-time HTML generation.

