ngOnInit
  --> runs automatically when a component is initialized (loaded)
  --> used to initialiae values
  --> set defualt values
  --> used for api calls
  --> used for building logic
  
  Constructor → ngOnInit → UI Render

---------------------------------------------------------------

ngOnChanges
  --> Whenever an input property changes
  --> It is used in a child component when data comes from a parent component

Parent Component
.ts
  name = 'Ragu';
.html
  <app-child [userName]="name"></app-child>

Child Component
  
import { Component, Input, OnChanges, SimpleChanges } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: `<p>{{ userName }}</p>`
})
export class ChildComponent implements OnChanges {

  @Input() userName: string = '';

  ngOnChanges(changes: SimpleChanges) {
    console.log(changes);
  }

}


Parent sends data → userName
Child receives via @Input
If value changes → ngOnChanges() runs automatically

---------------------------------------------------------------

ngDoCheck
  -->Every time Angular runs change detection

when does it run
✔ Button click
✔ Input typing
✔ API response
✔ Timer / async events
✔ Any UI update

---------------------------------------------------------------

ngAfterContentInit
  -->When you pass content inside a component tag, Angular inserts it using:

👉 <ng-content>

After that insertion → ngAfterContentInit() runs

Parent Component
<app-child>
  <p>This is projected content</p>
</app-child>

Child component
  
import { Component, AfterContentInit } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: `
    <h2>Child Component</h2>
    <ng-content></ng-content>
  `
})
export class ChildComponent implements AfterContentInit {

  ngAfterContentInit() {
    console.log('Content projected!');
  }

}

LifeCycle Order

ngOnChanges
→ ngOnInit
→ ngDoCheck
→ ngAfterContentInit   ✅ (runs once)
→ ngAfterContentChecked (runs multiple times)

---------------------------------------------------------------

ngAfterContentChecked
  -->After Angular checks the projected content (ng-content)
  
Example

import { Component, AfterContentChecked } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: `<ng-content></ng-content>`
})
export class ChildComponent implements AfterContentChecked {

  ngAfterContentChecked() {
    console.log('Content checked!');
  }

}

---------------------------------------------------------------
ngAfterViewInit
  --> After the component’s view (HTML + child components) is fully initialized

Use it when you need:

✔ Access DOM elements
✔ Access child components
✔ Perform UI-related logic
✔ Work with @ViewChild

LifeCycle Order

ngOnChanges
→ ngOnInit
→ ngDoCheck
→ ngAfterContentInit
→ ngAfterContentChecked
→ ngAfterViewInit   ✅ (runs once)
→ ngAfterViewChecked (runs multiple times)

---------------------------------------------------------------
ngAfterViewChecked
  --> After Angular checks the component’s view (HTML + child components)
  --> never run api call in it, because the call same api infinite times.
🔹 When does it run?
✔ After view initialization
✔ After every change detection cycle
✔ After UI updates (clicks, typing, API response)

---------------------------------------------------------------
ngOnDestroy
  --> Just before a component is destroyed (removed from DOM)

✔ Unsubscribe from Observables
✔ Stop timers (setInterval, setTimeout)
✔ Remove event listeners
✔ Clean up WebSocket connections



